div.p:
Let us take the fourth assumption, the PDE reduces to . The Maple paper says:

1. subdivide the equation into subexpressions involving only one of {f, g};

2. build a list of candidates for f and for g with the solutions to these subexpressions;

3. build a list of pairs of candidates by taking one candidate from each list.

div.div:
Seems Planet is now fine. Anyways, here are some profiling results of arithmetic operations of dense matrix. I am working on level 0 currently. [1]
The profile results will be like this- for each operation, the first one is the profile of previous implementation, the second is the profile of new ones and the third is the profile of new one *with last call to Matrix removed*.
For example, I am doing manipulations by first converting matrices to lists. Suppose "result" is the resultant list of the matrix. Then second profiles will be the implementations with returns Matrix(result) and the third ones will return just result.
All the third profiles will be discussed later.
a = Matrix([[3, 4, 5], [6, 7, 8], [9, 10, 11]])
b = Matrix([[4, 5, 6], [7, 8, 9], [10, 11, 12]])
