Conclusion : Not worth it.
What is really interesting now is that the third profiles are outperforming others by a huge margin. It turns out that _handle_creation_matrix is takes quite a lot of calls to execute itself. This I think is one of the significant bottlenecks in the current matrix code.
It turns out that if we somehow manage to make a more efficient data structure for dense matrix, we can speed up things significantly.
[1] https://github.com/sympy/sympy/pull/2248

I spent the last couple of days experimenting with alternate implementation of various algorithms. Here are the results--
for three implementations of sparse*sparse-- _mulspsp, _mulspsp2, _mulspsp3, on two matrices
a = SparseMatrix(3, 4, {(0, 0): 1, (0, 1): 2, (2, 2): 3})
b = SparseMatrix(4, 3, {(0, 0): 2, (0, 2): 4, (1, 2): 5})
