The new implementations of _applyfunc and scaler*sparse give little improvements but the code is simpler and thus less chances for error.
All the code can be found at the latest commit of https://github.com/sympy/sympy/pull/2206. Also written there is the rationale of using csr internally.

font.font:
This problem was one of the questions in my Advanced Dynamics class, so I know that this solution is correct. We can integrate this in Matlab using the ode suite. For e.g. we can use ode45. For this, we need to define the numbers for the problem and pack them so that we can pass them to the ODE file.
>> m = 1; L = 1; g = 10; I = m*L^2/12;
>> params.m = m; params.I = I; params.L = L; params.g = g;

Then we need to define the initial conditions of the system and the timespan for integration.
>> StateVar0 = [3*pi/4; 0];
>> tmax = 10;
>> tlist = linspace(0,tmax,1000);

I prefer using the anonymous functions to pass extra parameters to the system.
>> TargetODE = @(t,statevars) SlidingLadder_ODE(t,statevars,params);
Finally we execute the code to get output.
>> [tlist,statevars] = ode45(TargetODE,tlist,StateVar0,options);

div.p:
$$
\phi(t) = \begin{cases}
1 / (1 + \exp(-t)) \text{ if } t > 0 \\
\exp(t) / (1 + \exp(t)) \text{ if } t \leq 0\\
\end{cases}
$$
